  "articleSummary": "This article argues that **squash merge** is superior to **rebase** for team-based Git workflows, framing the debate as a \"deathmatch\" with \"religious fervor.\" The author analyzes the two strategies through the lens of commit purpose (checkpoint vs. curated art) and compares their pros/cons: rebase offers power but risks endless conflicts, broken permalinks, and lost PR comments, while squash merge is simpler, non-destructive, and lets Git optimize merges. The tone is analytical and opinionated, targeting developers and teams seeking a practical, low-risk workflow. Recurring metaphors include \"engineering theater\" and \"black belt in git fu\" to critique rebase's complexity.",
